  "raw_html": "<button type='button' role='link' class='btn btn-link p-0 text-start' id='link_5' aria-label=\" Geeta versus The State of Karnataka pdf\"  class='noToken' href='#' onclick=javascript:open_pdf('5','2025','2025_10_44_57','2025INSC1089'); ><font size='4'> <strong>GEETA<span class='fst-italic'> versus </span>THE STATE OF KARNATAKA </strong>- <span class='escrText'>[2025] 10 S.C.R. 44</span><span class='ncDisplay'>2025 INSC 1089</span><input type='hidden' id='cnr' value=ESCR010004062025></button></font><br><strong>Coram : B.V. NAGARATHNA<sup style=\"color: #268e97;font-size: 22px;top: 0;\" class=\"tooltip-sup\" data-tooltip=\"Author\">*</sup>, K.V. VISWANATHAN</strong><br> Issue for Consideration Whether the conviction of the appellant u/s.306, IPC is sustainable; was the evidence against the appellant of such nature that the overt acts attributed to her left the deceased-victim with no option except to commit suicide. Headnotes&dagger; Penal Code, 1860 &ndash; when not attracted &ndash; Deceased-victim and the first accused-appellant were immediate neighbours however, they were not on cordial terms and used to be at loggerheads &ndash; Case of the prosecution that victim took tuition classes in her house and that there used to be persistent noise<br><strong class='caseDetailsTD' ><span style='color:#212F3D' > Decision Date :</span><font color='green'> 09-09-2025</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Case No :</span><font color='green'> CRIMINAL APPEAL No. 1044/2018</font><span style='color:#212F3D' > | Disposal Nature :</span><font color='green'> Appeal(s) allowed</font>   <span style='color:#212F3D' > |  Bench :</span><font color='green'> 2 Judges</font></strong><div class='row my-1 mt-2 border bg-light'><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn btn-outline-secondary btn-sm my-1' onclick=open_splitview('5','2025','2025_10_44_57','2025INSC1089','S')><i <i class='fas fa-columns me-2'></i>Split view</a></div><div class='col-auto'><a href='#' class='btn b